  "articleSummary": "The article argues that adding more engineers to a late project is counterproductive due to the O(n²) growth of communication paths (n(n-1)/2) and the 3–6 month ramp-up time for new hires, which drains existing team focus. It cites Brooks’ Law, research from Microsoft DevDiv and *Accelerate*, and Amazon’s “two-pizza team” rule to show that smaller, autonomous teams outperform larger ones. The tone is analytical with a critical edge, using recurring metaphors like “coordination tax” and “mentorship tax.” The intended audience is engineering managers and technical leads facing deadline pressure.",
